Optimize this O(n^2) dedup and report the improvement:

function dedup(a){ return a.filter((x, i) => a.indexOf(x) === i); }

Give me the faster version.

Use a `Set` — it makes membership/insertion O(1) average, turning the whole thing from O(n²) into O(n).

```js
function dedup(a) {
  return [...new Set(a)];
}
```

That's the whole optimization. `Set` already deduplicates on insertion and preserves first-seen order, so spreading it back into an array gives you the same result your `filter` produced.

If you need to keep it as an explicit filter (e.g. for custom equality), the same idea applies with a seen-set:

```js
function dedup(a) {
  const seen = new Set();
  return a.filter(x => !seen.has(x) && seen.add(x));
}
```

**The improvement**

| | Original (`indexOf`) | `Set` version |
|---|---|---|
| Time | **O(n²)** — `indexOf` scans the array for every element | **O(n)** — one pass, O(1) lookups |
| Space | O(n) (output) | O(n) (the set + output) |

Why it's faster: `a.indexOf(x)` walks the array from the start on every iteration, so n elements × up-to-n scan = n² comparisons. The `Set` replaces that linear scan with a hash lookup, collapsing it to a single linear pass.

**Rough magnitude:** at n = 1,000 you go from ~1,000,000 comparisons to ~1,000 — about a 1000× drop in work; the gap widens linearly with n (at n = 10,000 it's ~10,000×).

**One caveat** — these aren't *exactly* equivalent for `NaN`: `indexOf(NaN)` returns `-1`, so the original drops all `NaN`s entirely, whereas `Set` treats `NaN` as equal to itself and keeps one. The `Set` behavior is almost always the one you actually want. Equality is otherwise identical (`SameValueZero` vs `===` differ only on `NaN`).

